1Ô∏è‚É£ Introduction to python:
print("Hello, Python!") 

-> identation in python ( Python automatically detects indentation (blocks)):
print("Hello, Python!")  # Simple print

if True:
    print("Python uses indentation instead of braces")

2Ô∏è‚É£ variables and comments in python:
name = "Adeeba"  # Variable (hashtag a comment)
age = 20
print("Name:", name, "Age:", age)

3Ô∏è‚É£ Type casting:
num_str = "100"
num_int = int(num_str)  # string to int
num_float = float(num_str)  # string to float

print(num_int, type(num_int))
print(num_float, type(num_float))

4Ô∏è‚É£ Rules for writing variables
## Camel Case
studentName = "Ali"

# Snake Case
student_name = "Sara"

# Pascal Case
StudentName = "Ahmed"

# Legal Variables
x = 10
_y = 20
z2 = 30

# Illegal Variables (will give error if uncommented)
# 2x = 10
# my-name = "Test"

5Ô∏è‚É£ Python Statements
x = 10
y = 20
if x < y:
    print("x is less than y")
else:
    print("x is greater than or equal to y")

6Ô∏è‚É£ Data Types in python
üîπ 1. Numeric Types
a) Integer (int)
x = 10
y = -5
print("Integer:", x, "Type:", type(x))
print("Integer:", y, "Type:", type(y))

b) Float (float)
a = 10.5
b = -3.14
print("Float:", a, "Type:", type(a))
print("Float:", b, "Type:", type(b))

c) Complex (complex)
c1 = 2 + 3j
c2 = complex(5, -1)
print("Complex:", c1, "Type:", type(c1))
print("Complex:", c2, "Type:", type(c2))

üîπ 2. Sequence Types
a) String (str)
name = "Adeeba"
print("String:", name, "Type:", type(name))

# Multi-line string
text = """This is
a multi-line
string"""
print(text)

b) List (list)
fruits = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
print("List of fruits:", fruits, "Type:", type(fruits))
print("List of numbers:", numbers)

c) Tuple (tuple)
coords = (10, 20)
colors = ("red", "green", "blue")
print("Tuple:", coords, "Type:", type(coords))
print("Tuple:", colors)

d) Range (range)
r = range(0, 5)  # 0 to 4
for i in r:
    print(i, end=" ")
print("\nType:", type(r))

üîπ 3. Set Types
a) Set (set)
my_set = {1, 2, 3, 4, 4, 2}  # duplicates removed
print("Set:", my_set, "Type:", type(my_set))

b) Frozen Set (frozenset)
fset = frozenset([1, 2, 3, 3])
print("Frozen Set:", fset, "Type:", type(fset))

üîπ 4. Mapping Type
a) Dictionary (dict)
person = {"name": "Adeeba", "age": 20, "city": "Karachi"}
print("Dictionary:", person, "Type:", type(person))

# Access values
print("Name:", person["name"])
print("Age:", person.get("age"))

üîπ 5. Boolean Type (bool)
a = True
b = False
print("Boolean a:", a, "Type:", type(a))
print("Boolean b:", b, "Type:", type(b))

üîπ 6. None Type
x = None
print("NoneType:", x, "Type:", type(x))

7Ô∏è‚É£ Global vs Local Variables
x = 10  # Global variable

def demo():
    x = 5  # Local variable
    print("Inside function:", x)

demo()
print("Outside function:", x)

8Ô∏è‚É£ Strings
üîπ Strings
str1 = "Hello"
str2 = "World"

üîπ Concatenation
greeting = str1 + " " + str2
print(greeting)

üîπ Modifying Strings
text = "hello world"
print(text.upper())   # HELLO WORLD
print(text.lower())  # Hello world
print(text.replace("world", "Python"))  # hello Python

üîπ String Methods
-> keyword in , not in , using in and not in keyword in if statement
text = "Python123"
# Check if a substring exists
if "Python" in text:
    print("'Python' is present in text")
else:
    print("'Python' is NOT present in text")
#using in keyword in if statement:
if "Python" in text:
    print('Python' is present in text")

# Check if a substring does NOT exist
if "Java" not in text:
    print("'Java' is NOT present in text")
else:
    print("'Java' is present in text")

9Ô∏è‚É£ Operators in python
# Arithmetic
print(5 + 3, 5 - 3, 5 * 3, 5 / 3, 5 % 3, 5 ** 3)

# Comparison
print(5 > 3, 5 == 3, 5 != 3)

# Logical
print(True and False, True or False, not True)



